28. Fourth Arqument. What natural Reason so requires to be done by us, that if it be not done, there i's fault and gunt, is obliga- tory on the Conscience: for in the Conscience, resides the sense of fault and guilt. But natural Reason does in this way require us to obey Human Laws3 so that if we do not do so, we are conscious of fault and guilt. Therefore Human Laws 616 obligatory on 1116 Con- sc1ence.

29. Fifth Aryument. That whereof the transgression necessarily draws along with it a violation of the Law of God, obliges the Con- science; for no one can with 6 1111016 Conscience violate the Law of God, which is the Rule of Conscience. But the transgression of any law rightly constituted by man, does necessarily draw along with it a violation of the Law of God3 namely, of that General Rule in which God enjoins obedience to the powers that be. Therefore laws rightly constituted by men do oblige the Conscience.
